Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: UBA, Kenya Reinsurance, Naiade Resorts

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-04-15T15:58:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-15/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenya-reinsurance-naiade-resorts.html
Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall
Index (FTN098)  declined 0.8 percent to 869.25 by the 4 p.m. close in
Windhoek, the lowest level since March 29 and the first weekly
fall in four.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index rose for the
fourth day, advancing 0.5 percent to 25,036.75 by the 2:30 p.m.
close in Lagos, according to a statement on the bourse’s
website, climbing for the first week in three, adding 1.2
percent in five days. The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index
fell 0.3 percent to 1,055.45 by the 3 p.m. close in Accra,
slumping for the second week. Kenya’s All-Share Index advanced
for the first day in three, adding 0.6 percent to 74.53 by the 3
p.m. end of trading in Nairobi. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index slid
for the first day in three, dropping 0.2 percent to 2,048.98 at
the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis . That was the biggest one-day
retreat since March 18.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Kenya Airways Ltd. (KNAL)  , sub-Saharan Africa’s third-
biggest airline, rose for a second day, jumping 2.75 shillings,
or 8 percent, to 37.25 shillings, the most since Aug. 2, after
saying yesterday it will buy nine new Boeing Corp. 787 aircraft
with an option to purchase four more planes.  “Confirming the delivery schedules is positive news
because one of their challenges has been an aging fleet and
capacity constraints,” Gregory Waweru, an analyst at Nairobi-
based Kestrel Capital East Africa Ltd., said in a phone
interview today.  Kenya Reinsurance Corp. (KNRE KN), a state-owned reinsurer,
rose for the first day in nine, advancing 1 percent to 9.8
shillings, after naming Jadiah Mwarania as its managing
director.  “It brings in some element of certainty, which is quite
good for the market,” Eric Musau, an analyst at Nairobi-based
African Alliance Securities Kenya Ltd., said by phone today.  Naiade Resorts Ltd. (NRL)  , Mauritius’s third-largest
hotel operator by market value, rose for a fifth day, adding 1.8
rupees, or 6.6 percent, to 28.9 rupees, on speculation third-
quarter profit improved.  “Naiade is rising on hopefully better results for its
third quarter through March as it coincides with the second-half
of the peak tourism season,” Imrith Ramtohul, a senior
investment manager who oversees 6 billion rupees ($216 million)
in assets at Mauritius Union Assurance Co., said by phone.  United Bank for Africa Plc (UBA)  ,  Nigeria ’s fifth-
largest lender by market value, gained 5 kobo, or 0.6 percent,
to 8.05 naira after saying it plans to issue bonus shares and as
profit more than doubled to 3.9 billion naira ($25 million) in
the first quarter through March.  To contact the reporter on this story:
